tweet: 8a  This is an unexamined position. To claim national governments and corporations are somehow equivalent in the wielding of power... I'll believe this when Google murders people with drones and Bezos imprisons me for smoking a plant.

tweet: 8) "I dislike the state because I dislike any concentration of power which is unaccountable and unanswerable to the people.   But equally, equally, I despise the central authority of Google, of Facebook, of private sources of concentrated power. "

tweet: 6b It doesn't matter who controls the money printer. The act of legally compelling a populace to trade with fiat while debasing that fiat is itself theft. A different thief with different justifications doesn't make currency debasement magically ethical.
name: Erik Voorhees

tweet: 6) "My criticism with [central banks] is not that they have the power to expand and contract the supply of money, but the way they use it. "  6a This is the old "if only our guys were in power, things would be better... if only WE could manipulate money instead of THEM"
name: Erik Voorhees

tweet: 5a2 Reality: the US was built on apolitical money (gold), and this was the standard until 1971.   Sure, you can blame Great Depression on gold if you also give credit to gold for the entire industrial revolution and the rise of America from agrarian backwater to world power.
name: Erik Voorhees

tweet: 5) "The one time we had historical records when we had a fixed supply of money, an apolitical money, was 1929. "  5a This is deceptive... as though there was some tiny example in which we "experimented" with an apolitical money and that was 1929 which caused Depression.
name: Erik Voorhees

tweet: 4) "Imagine how much worse [COVID] would have been if we had money that could not be expanded rapidly as a result of a political decision."   4a Pristine example of Bastiat's "unseen." The unseen cost here is the years of price inflation now decimating the people. Yanis ignores.
name: Erik Voorhees

tweet: 3) "We need authorities that have the capacity to expand/contract the money supply, in response to economic upturns and downturns. "  3a The existence of this power is relatively recent and during its time we've seen wealth disparity and global debt skyrocket. Do we *need* that?
name: Erik Voorhees

tweet: 2) "The main reason [capitalism requires fiat] is that the quantity of money has to be adjustable"  2a Again, the entire 19th century (arguably capitalism's greatest century) occurred without an adjustable money supply.
name: Erik Voorhees

tweet: 1a2 Fiat money is a parasite currently living within an otherwise healthy capitalist host. Can crypto replace fiat? We shall see, but if it does, capitalism will rejoice.  It's absurd to claim a market-based economy should have a centrally-planned money.

tweet: 1a Yanis begins upon a foundation of sophistry.   He claims capitalism requires fiat: demonstrably false  considering modern fiat money only began in 1971 (prior it was gold). I believe capitalism existed (indeed thrived) for at least 250 years in US prior to 1971.
